Some commands return additional information when encountering an error. In this specific case, the `shardCollection` command contains a list of indexes and a proposed key in its result if the shard key is not already present as an index:

```
mongos> db.adminCommand({shardCollection: 'doctrine_odm_tests.sharded.one', key: { k: 1 }})
{
    "proposedKey" : {
        "k" : 1
    },
    "curIndexes" : [
        {
            "v" : 1,
            "key" : {
                "_id" : 1
            },
            "name" : "_id_",
            "ns" : "doctrine_odm_tests.sharded.one"
        }
    ],
    "ok" : 0,
    "errmsg" : "please create an index that starts with the shard key before sharding."
}
```

However, when running this command through the driver, the resulting `MongoDB\Driver\Exception\RuntimeException` does not contain the `proposedKey` and `curIndexes` fields. This makes it impossible to use the command result to get the proper index one should create for the shard key.

### Description

I experience a 500ms wait time in case mongodb server is not running / stopped.
But weird thing is that first request fails in < 1 ms but subsequent requests all take at least 500ms.
It doesn't matter if the php script waits or the request just takes that time. 500ms seems to be some fixed value here.

Please check my PHP script below and try by yourself. No MongoDB server required.
Feel free to add timeout parameters but I didn't had any luck with them.

### Environment

/usr/local/etc/php/7.1/conf.d/ext-mongodb.ini,
mongodb
mongodb support => enabled
mongodb version => 1.2.2
mongodb stability => stable
libmongoc version => 1.5.0
libbson version => 1.5.0
mongodb.debug => no value => no value

### Test Script


```
<?php

function fireAndMeasureTime(\MongoDB\Driver\Manager $manager, $number) {
    $startMicro = microtime(true);
    try {
        $result = $manager->executeCommand('local', new \MongoDB\Driver\Command(['ping' => 1]));
    } catch(\Throwable $exception) {
        echo $number.". query failed with " . $exception->getMessage() . "\n";
    }
    echo $number.". query took " . (microtime(true) - $startMicro)*1000 . "ms\n";
}

// Assuming you have no local mongodb instance running there.
$manager = new \MongoDB\Driver\Manager('mongodb://127.0.0.1:3000');

fireAndMeasureTime($manager, 1); // fails very fast:  < 1ms

// Try to connect to a port running nothing.
$manager = new \MongoDB\Driver\Manager('mongodb://127.0.0.1:12345');

fireAndMeasureTime($manager, 2); // fails very fast too: < 1ms

fireAndMeasureTime($manager, 3); // Second request on same port failes after 500ms.

usleep(200*1000); // it doesn't matter where the 500ms above are spent, so spend some in php to show effect.

fireAndMeasureTime($manager, 4); // ~300ms only because we waited 200 ms before

// switch port back and forth
$manager = new \MongoDB\Driver\Manager('mongodb://127.0.0.1:3000');
$manager = new \MongoDB\Driver\Manager('mongodb://127.0.0.1:12345');

fireAndMeasureTime($manager, 5); // still slow, as if the 500ms wait time is required.

// switch back to first connection (has been used more than 500ms ago)
$manager = new \MongoDB\Driver\Manager('mongodb://127.0.0.1:3000');

fireAndMeasureTime($manager, 6); // fast again, 500ms wait window is over on this connection.

```

